===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|ermine}}, {{m|enm|ermin}}, {{m|enm|ermyn}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|ermin}}, {{m|fro|ermine}}, {{m|fro|hermine}}.

There are two main theories for the origin of {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|ermine}}. Germanic origin is suggested via {{cog|odt|*harmino|t=stoat skin}}, from {{m|odt|*harmo|t=stoat, weasel}} (compare Dutch dialectal {{m|nl|herm}}), from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*harmǭ}}, {{m|gem-pro|*harmô}} (compare Old English {{m|ang|hearma}}, Old High German {{m|goh|harmo}} ({{m|goh|harmin|pos=a}}, obsolete German {{m|de|Harm}}), from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*ḱormō}} (compare Romansch {{m|rm|carmun}}, obsolete Lithuanian {{m|lt|šarmuõ}}). Romance sources identify the animal with the corresponding word for [[Armenian]], possibly from {{cog|ML.|[[mūs]] [[Armenius]]||Armenian mouse}} or a posterior compound.

